<h2>What is a URL?</h2>

<p>
  A URL (Uniform Resource Locator) most commonly references web pages 
  (<a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol">HTTP</a>)
  but can also apply to file transfer
  (<a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_Transfer_Protocol">FTP</a>), 
  email 
  (<a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mailto">mailto</a>), 
  database access
  (<a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open_Database_Connectivity">ODBC</a>) 
  and many other applications.
  An HTTP URL can also describe the location of external resources such as images,
  style sheets,
  scripts
  and even a specific section within an HTML document.
  Complete or at least partial URLs appear in the address bar of most web browsers.
</p>

