<h2>8. Fragment Identifier</h2>

<p>
  Within an HTML document
  (web page)
  individual sections can be identified as bookmarks.
  If a bookmark is included as part of the URL,
  web browsers will jump directly to that point.
  This specificity can be very helpful on web pages with a significant amount of content.
  Fragment identifiers are also the basis for navigation options within
  <a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single-page_application">
    single-page applications
  </a>.
</p>

<h2>SEO Friendly URLs</h2>

<p>
  If SEO (Search Engine Optimization) is a goal of your website,
  here is how to make the most of URLs.
</p>

<h3>HTTPS</h3>

<p>
  Use the HTTPS protocol instead of HTTP.
  Besides protecting the privacy of your visitors,
  <a target="_blank" href="https://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2014/08/https-as-ranking-signal.html">
    Google has publicly announced
  </a>
  they are giving a small SEO bonus to websites that correctly employ HTTPS on all pages.
  To learn more about this,
  please read
  <a href="https://cascadingmedia.com/insites/2015/01/https-everywhere.html">
    HTTPS Everywhere
  </a>.
</p>

<h3>Subdomains</h3>

<p>
  If you choose to use subdomains,
  be careful because most search engines treat each subdomain as a separate entity.
  This dilutes the effectiveness of any domain authority your website has earned.
</p>

<h3>Keyword Separators</h3>

<p>
  Use hyphens (-) to separate path/page keywords and not underscores (_).
  This is because words separated by hyphens are easier for search engines to parse.
</p>

<h3>Fragment Identifiers</h3>

<p>
  Use of fragment identifiers may help search engines better understand page structure.
  If a fragment identifier contains more than one word,
  separate the words with a hyphen.
</p>

<h3>URL Length</h3>

<p>
  Keyword effectiveness decreases as URL length increases.
  Keep your URLs keyword rich but concise.
  Remove unimportant words like:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>the</li>
  <li>a/an</li>
  <li>with</li>
  <li>etc.</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Minimizing URL length is another good reason not to use a www subdomain.
</p>

<h3>Query Strings</h3>

<p>
  Search engines prefer clean, human readable URLs.
  If your website&#8217;s markup is generated by server-side scripts,
  some URLs might look something like this:
</p>

<pre><code>https://example.com/index.php?article=1234
</pre></code>

<p>
  This URL would be far more effective in search engines if it read:
</p>

<pre><code>https://example.com/articles/create-seo-friendly-url
</code></pre>

<p>
  The second example is longer
  but it describes the page content far more effectively.
</p>

<h2>Content is Key</h2>

<p>
  As a parting SEO thought,
  remember that technical optimizations like these are helpful
  but the key to ranking higher in search engines
  is to publish high quality content
  on a regular basis.
  With quality content comes inbound links,
  which leads to higher search engine rankings.
</p>

